     Science in School email alert 8: May 2008 
     http://www.scienceinschool.org/alerts/alert8 
     <p class="mainNormalText">Dear <em>Science in School</em> subscribers,</p> <p class="mainNormalText">I am pleased to inform you that the eighth issue of <em>Science in School</em> is now available to read and download at <a href="http://www.scienceinschool.org">www.scienceinschool.org</a>. Those of you who have subscribed to a print copy should receive it soon. If you havenÕt yet subscribed, you can do so (free) online: <a href="/subscriptions">www.scienceinschool.org/subscriptions</a></p> <p class="mainSectionTitle">Contents</p> <p class="mainNormalText">Our feature article takes us into space. <a href="/2008/issue8/bernardopatti/">Bernardo Patti</a> from ESA spoke to Anna-Lynn Wegener about the Columbus mission. This efficiently packed research laboratory with minimal space has now joined the International Space Station (ISS) and will help us to learn more about biology, physiology, fluid dynamics and material sciences both in space and on Earth. The ISSÕs most recent addition, however, has been the transport shuttle Jules Verne. This <a href="/2008/issue8/atv/">Automated Transfer Vehicle</a> has been the first one to dock completely automatically. The technology and required training behind this is amazing Ð Adam Williams gives us a flavour of their extent.</p><p><a href="http://www.scienceinschool.org/alerts/alert8" target="_blank">read more</a></p> 
